5. Changing all text to lowercase, removing punctuation and numbers¶

In [36]:
# defining a function to change all text to lowercase, correctly format any apostrophes, removing any numbers and punctuation
# code source: https://github.com/adashofdata/nlp-in-python-tutorial/blob/master/1-Data-Cleaning.ipynb
def cleaning(text):
    #     lowercase
    text = text.lower()
    #     correctly formatting any apostrophes
    text = re.sub("â€™", "'", text)
    #     removing any punctuation
    text = re.sub("[%s]" % re.escape(string.punctuation), "", text)
    #     removing any numbers
    text = re.sub("\w*\d\w*", "", text)
    return text

# apply function to our dataframe and keeping the title, text and fake column
df_clean = pd.DataFrame({"title_text": df["title_text"].apply(cleaning), "fake": df["fake"]})

1 & 4. Count the number of instances of each word class and number of unique words used¶

In [38]:
# feature extraction by counting instances of each word class and getting the number of unique words used (i.e. vocabulary)
# code source: https://www.nltk.org/book/ch05.html
for i in range(len(df_clean)):
    tokens_text = word_tokenize(df_clean.iloc[i,0])
    text_tagged = pos_tag(tokens_text, tagset='universal')
    tag_freq_den = FreqDist(tag for (word,tag) in text_tagged)
    
    for key in tag_freq_den.keys():
        df_clean.loc[i, key] = tag_freq_den[key]

    unique = set(tokens_text)
    df_clean.loc[i, "vocab"] = len(unique)
        
# replace NA values with 0
df_clean.fillna(0, inplace=True)

2. Drop any word classes that appear less than once per article on average¶

In [39]:
# dropping word classes which has less total number of instances than the number of observations (i.e. on average appears in less than 1 time in each text), and the "X", "." and "NUM" columns which represent any abbreviations, punctuation and numbers respectively
cols_exclude = ["title_text", "fake", "vocab"]
cols_to_drop = ["X", ".", "NUM"]

for col in df_clean:
    if col not in cols_exclude:
        sum_of_instances = df_clean[col].sum()
        if sum_of_instances <= len(df_clean):
            cols_to_drop.append(col)


df_word_class = df_clean.drop(columns=cols_to_drop)

# normalising word class counts by number of total words in remaining word classes
df_word_class_norm = df_word_class.copy(deep=True)

# iterating over observations, calculating the total number of words and normalising each word label by the total number of words for that observation
for i in range(len(df_word_class_norm)):
    total_words = 0
    #     iterate over word label columns to get total number of words
    #     note: getting the total number of words using the len() function on the title_text column is not entirely accurate as some columns were dropped earlier
    for j in range(2, 11):
        total_words += df_word_class_norm.iloc[i, j]
    #     after getting total number of words, iterate over word label columns and normalise each column

# dropping any instances where it is divided by 0

5. Outlier Exclusion - Tagging any identified observations as outliers¶

In [42]:
# identifying any outliers based on proportion of sentence falling in each word label class
df_word_class_norm_2 = df_word_class_norm.copy(deep=True)

# storing column names, creating fields to store outlier tagging and getting means and standard deviation of each word label class
col_names = []
is_outlier_names = []
col_means = []
col_std = []
for col in df_word_class_norm:
    if col != "title_text" and col != "fake":
        outlier_col = "isOutlier" + col
        df_word_class_norm_2[outlier_col] = 0
        col_names.append(col)
        is_outlier_names.append(outlier_col)
        col_means.append(df_word_class_norm_2[col].mean())
        col_std.append(df_word_class_norm_2[col].std())
        
# if proportion of the word class label is greater or less than +-2 standard deviations of the mean of that word class label, tag it as an outlier
for i in range(len(df_word_class_norm_2)):
    for j in range(len(col_names)):
        if df_word_class_norm_2.loc[i, col_names[j]] >= col_means[j] + 2*col_std[j] or df_word_class_norm_2.loc[i, col_names[j]] <= col_means[j] - 2*col_std[j]:
            df_word_class_norm_2.loc[i, is_outlier_names[j]] = 1

We look to tag any outliers to remove from the dataset. Here we defined an outlier to be any point which are +-2 standard deviation away from the mean. Extreme examples can include entries which are only made up of a single word class type; resulting in a nonsensical sentence to begin with and hence should be removed.

6. Getting polarity and subjectivity of text using textblob¶

In [44]:
# setting up columns to store polarity and subjectivity
df_word_class_cleaned["polarity"] = 0
df_word_class_cleaned["subjectivity"] = 0

# getting polarity and subjectivity of each observation using TextBlob
for i in range(len(df_word_class_cleaned)):
    b = TextBlob(df_word_class_cleaned.iloc[i,0])
    df_word_class_cleaned.loc[i, "polarity"] = b.sentiment[0]
    df_word_class_cleaned.loc[i, "subjectivity"] = b.sentiment[1]

3. Model Fitting¶

Fitting 2-component Logistic Regression¶

In [60]:
# fitting logistic regression using the 2 principal components
lr_model_pca_2 = LogisticRegression()
lr_model_pca_2.fit(df_comp_2, training_set_y)
lr_training_pred_pca_2 = lr_model_pca_2.predict(df_comp_2)

# getting the coefficients to plot the decision boundary
intercept_pca = lr_model_pca_2.intercept_[0]
comp_1_coef = lr_model_pca_2.coef_[0][0]
comp_2_coef = lr_model_pca_2.coef_[0][1]
dec_bound_c = -intercept_pca/comp_2_coef
dec_bound_m = -comp_1_coef/comp_2_coef
In [61]:
# plot the observations by its principal components and the classification with the decision boundary
# code source: https://scipython.com/blog/plotting-the-decision-boundary-of-a-logistic-regression-model/
xmin, xmax = -6, 6
ymin, ymax = -5, 6
xd = np.array([xmin, xmax])
yd = dec_bound_m*xd + dec_bound_c
plt.plot(xd, yd, 'k', lw=1, ls='--')
plt.scatter(comp_1_f, comp_2_f, c="darkorange", alpha=1)
plt.scatter(comp_1_r, comp_2_r, c="darkblue", alpha=0.1)
plt.fill_between(xd, yd, ymin, color='tab:orange', alpha=0.15)
plt.fill_between(xd, yd, ymax, color='b', alpha=0.15)

plt.xlim(xmin, xmax)
plt.ylim(ymin, ymax)
plt.ylabel('PC2')
plt.xlabel('PC1')
plt.legend(["Decision Boundary", "Fake News", "Real News"], loc=2)

plt.show()

Indeed, given the significant of overlap between fake and real news, a line may not suffice as decision boundary. In addition, from the plot, there's likely to be fairly large amounts of false positives and relatively lower amounts of false negatives due to the overlap.

In [98]:
# setting up function to plot plane
# code source:https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36232334/plotting-3d-decision-boundary-from-linear-svm
z = lambda x, y: (-lr_model_pca_3.intercept_[0] - lr_model_pca_3.coef_[0][0] * x - lr_model_pca_3.coef_[0][1] * y) / lr_model_pca_3.coef_[0][2]
tmp = np.linspace(-6, 6, 48)
x, y = np.meshgrid(tmp, tmp)

# plotting a scatterplot to get an idea of the distribution of the classes by the 3 principal components
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))
ax = fig.add_subplot(projection='3d')
ax.plot_surface(x, y, z(x, y), alpha=0.4)
ax.scatter(comp_1_f, comp_2_f, comp_3_f, c="darkorange", alpha=0.1)
ax.scatter(comp_1_r, comp_2_r, comp_3_r, c="darkblue", alpha=0.1)
ax.set_xlabel('PC1')
ax.set_ylabel('PC2')
ax.set_zlabel('PC3')

# rotating the view of the 3d scatterplot
ax.view_init(15, 50)
plt.draw()

plt.show()

The decision boundary in the 3D space (i.e. a plane) is slightly harder to interpet compared to the 2D decision boundary (i.e. a line) as it's in the 3D space. The dark blue points are the observations tagged as real news while the orange ones are tagged as fake. In addition, the dull-toned blue plane represents the decision boundary in the 3D space.

Fitting 2-component Decision Tree¶

It is noted that a decision tree benefits from higher values of maximum depth but this will result in a trade-off between interpretability and complexity. In addition, deeper trees also run the risk of overfitting.
